==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fōt-'', from Indo-European ''*pēd-, pōd-'' ‘foot’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''fōt'', Old Saxon ''fōt'' (Dutch [[voet]]), Old High German [[fuoz]] (German [[Fuß]]), Old Norse ''fōtr'' (Swedish, Norwegian ''fot''), Gothic [[𐍆𐍉𐍄𐌿𐍃]].  The IE root was also the source of Sanskrit [[पद्]], Greek [[πους]] (gen. ''ποδος''), Latin [[pes]] (gen. ''pedis'').

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /fo:t/

===Noun===
'''fōt''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''fēt''')
# ''(Anatomy)''  A [[foot]]
# [[Pace]] or [[tread]]
# ''(Prosody)''  A [[foot]]
# A unit of length, especially equal to a third of a [[yard]]

